            <pb facs="#f0001" />
            <p>
                <hi rendition="#k">Von Humboldt.</hi>&#x2014;The <hi rendition="#i">Prussian Universal Gazette</hi><lb/>publishes the following letter:&#x2014;&#x201C; Whenever I find my<lb/>name quoted in an unfavourable manner, either in a political<lb/>or literary point of view, in the journals, I make it a point<lb/>to remain silent; but I break through that rule when any<lb/>calumny is directed against one of my intimate friends.<lb/>The <hi rendition="#i">Manheim Gazette</hi> of the 28th ult. announces the fol-<lb/>lowing, under the head Berlin:&#x2014;&#x2018; We have been informed<lb/>that M. Arago has declined to accept the Prussian Order of<lb/>Merit, and has sent it back. This report has been confirmed,<lb/>and M. Arago has written on the subject to Alexandre Von<lb/>Humboldt.&#x2019; This statement is as ridiculous as it is absurd.<lb/>The King of Prussia, after conferring the Order of Merit on<lb/>a number of persons unconnected with the army, simulta-<lb/>neously appointed knights of that order M. Arago, M. Le-<lb/>tronne, M. de Chateaubriand, M. Daguerre, M. Ingres, M.<lb/>Horace Vernet, and M. Gay Lussac. M. Arago was the first <lb/>who replied, on the 8th of June, 1842, that he accepted the<lb/>decoration. He wrote to me to that effect, in my capacity<lb/>of Chancellor of the new institution, and expressed himself<lb/>in terms which bespoke his satisfaction.</p>
            <closer>
                <salute>
                    <hi rendition="#et">&#x201C;<hi rendition="#k">Alexandre Von Humboldt.</hi></hi>
                </salute>
                <dateline>&#x201C;Berlin, Nov. 1, 1848.&#x201D;</dateline>
            </closer>
